## Example 1 — Cross-Sections of a Cube

A cube has side length 6 cm. Describe the cross-section for each cut:
(a) parallel to a face
(b) perpendicular to a face through the center
(c) through six edges to form a regular hexagon

### Step 1: Parallel to a Face

A plane parallel to a face of a cube slices a **square** with side length 6 cm.

$$\text{Area} = 6 \times 6 = 36 \text{ cm}^2$$

### Step 2: Perpendicular Through the Center

A vertical plane cutting through the center, perpendicular to a face, produces a **rectangle** with dimensions 6 cm × 6 cm (a square — same as the face).

If the cut is perpendicular but offset from center, the rectangle dimensions change but it remains a rectangle.

### Step 3: Regular Hexagonal Cross-Section

Cutting through all six edges symmetrically (at equal angles) produces a **regular hexagon**.

The side length of this hexagon is:

$$s = \frac{6\sqrt{2}}{2} = 3\sqrt{2} \approx 4.24 \text{ cm}$$

✅ Answer: (a) Square, 36 cm²; (b) Rectangle (square), 36 cm²; (c) Regular hexagon with side $3\sqrt{2}$ cm.

