## Example 2 — Cross-Sections of a Cylinder

A cylinder has radius 4 in and height 10 in. Describe and compute the area of each cross-section:
(a) parallel to the base
(b) perpendicular to the base
(c) at a 45° angle

### Step 1: Parallel to the Base

A horizontal plane slices a **circle** with radius 4 in.

$$\text{Area} = \pi(4)^2 = 16\pi \approx 50.27 \text{ in}^2$$

### Step 2: Perpendicular to the Base

A vertical plane through the center slices a **rectangle** with width = diameter = 8 in and height = 10 in.

$$\text{Area} = 8 \times 10 = 80 \text{ in}^2$$

### Step 3: At a 45° Angle

A plane at 45° slices an **ellipse**. The minor axis equals the diameter (8 in), and the major axis is stretched by the angle:

$$\text{Major axis} = \frac{8}{\cos(45°)} = \frac{8}{\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}} = 8\sqrt{2} \approx 11.31 \text{ in}$$

$$\text{Area of ellipse} = \pi \cdot \frac{8}{2} \cdot \frac{8\sqrt{2}}{2} = \pi \cdot 4 \cdot 4\sqrt{2} = 16\sqrt{2}\pi \approx 71.09 \text{ in}^2$$

✅ Answer: (a) Circle, $16\pi \approx 50.27$ in²; (b) Rectangle, 80 in²; (c) Ellipse, $16\sqrt{2}\pi \approx 71.09$ in².

