## Example 4 — Cavalieri's Principle Application

A slanted (oblique) cylinder has the same base radius 5 m and the same height 12 m as a right cylinder. Do they have the same volume?

### Step 1: Volume of the Right Cylinder

$$V_{\text{right}} = \pi(5)^2(12) = 300\pi \approx 942.48 \text{ m}^3$$

### Step 2: Apply Cavalieri's Principle

At every level (measured perpendicular to the bases), the cross-section of the oblique cylinder is a circle with the same radius as the right cylinder. Since the cross-sectional areas are equal at every height, the volumes are equal.

$$V_{\text{oblique}} = V_{\text{right}} = 300\pi$$

### Step 3: Verify with Formula

For any cylinder (right or oblique):

$$V = B \times h = \pi r^2 \times h_{\perp}$$

where $h_{\perp}$ is the perpendicular distance between the bases, not the slant height. ✓

✅ Answer: Yes — both cylinders have volume $300\pi \approx$ **942.48 m³**.

