## Example 5 — Real-World: 3D Printing Cross-Sections

A 3D printer builds objects layer by layer. A model of a sphere with radius 6 cm is printed with layers 0.2 mm thick. Describe the cross-section of each layer.

### Step 1: Cross-Section at Height $z$

A sphere centered at the origin with radius 6 satisfies $x^2 + y^2 + z^2 = 36$. At height $z$, the cross-section is a circle with radius:

$$r(z) = \sqrt{36 - z^2}$$

### Step 2: Varying Cross-Sections

| Height $z$ (cm) | Radius $r(z)$ (cm) | Area (cm²) |
|-----------------|-------------------|------------|
| 0 (equator) | $\sqrt{36} = 6$ | $36\pi \approx 113.10$ |
| 3 | $\sqrt{36 - 9} = \sqrt{27} \approx 5.20$ | $27\pi \approx 84.82$ |
| 5 | $\sqrt{36 - 25} = \sqrt{11} \approx 3.32$ | $11\pi \approx 34.56$ |
| 6 (top) | $\sqrt{36 - 36} = 0$ | $0$ |

### Step 3: Interpret

The layers start large at the equator and shrink toward the poles. The printer deposits material proportional to the cross-sectional area at each layer.

### Step 4: Volume from Layers

With 0.2 mm = 0.02 cm layers, there are $\frac{12}{0.02} = 600$ layers. Summing the cross-sectional areas times thickness approximates the volume:

$$V \approx \sum_{i=1}^{600} A(z_i) \cdot 0.02 \approx \frac{4}{3}\pi(6)^3 \approx 904.78 \text{ cm}^3$$

✅ Answer: Each layer is a circle whose radius decreases from 6 cm (equator) to 0 cm (poles). The printer approximates the sphere's volume of $\frac{4}{3}\pi(216) = 288\pi \approx$ **904.78 cm³**.

